<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1281,1413]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName box="[151,356,1281,1305]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Glossamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aprion">
<emphasis box="[151,356,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Glossamia aprion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only freshwater representative in the Kimberley of the large, typically marine, family 
<taxonomicName box="[151,292,1317,1341]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Apogonidae</taxonomicName>
. Widespread throughout the Kimberley, 
<taxonomicName box="[747,852,1317,1341]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Glossamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aprion">
<emphasis box="[747,852,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">G. aprion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a fragmented distribution but is common in the Fitzroy, Carson and Ord Rivers, with the species also reported from the Lawley, Durack and Pentecost Rivers (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1417,1440]" captionTargetBox="[262,1325,197,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-23@53.[257,1330,193,1396]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 37. Distribution of Glossamia aprion in the Kimberley." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
